<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1193,1397]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
This dark brown thrips (
<figureCitation box="[425,507,1193,1217]" captionStart="FIGURES 68 – 72" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1979,2002]" captionTargetBox="[212,1380,197,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[212,1381,193,1961]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 68 – 72. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. spinosus female 68 – 72: 68. Dorsal view; 69. Head and pronotum; 70. Fore wing; 71. Mesonotum and metanotum; 72. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280419/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[478,507,1193,1217]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="68.0">68</number>
</figureCitation>
) is remarkable in having largely dark fore wings, without the usual sub-basal pale area (
<figureCitation box="[214,299,1229,1253]" captionStart="FIGURES 68 – 72" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1979,2002]" captionTargetBox="[212,1380,197,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[212,1381,193,1961]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 68 – 72. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. spinosus female 68 – 72: 68. Dorsal view; 69. Head and pronotum; 70. Fore wing; 71. Mesonotum and metanotum; 72. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280419/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Fig. 
<number box="[267,299,1229,1253]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="70.0">70</number>
</figureCitation>
). Moreover, postocular setae pair III is longer than in any other Brazilian species, and pronotum and mesonotum have reticulate-striate sculpture (
<figureCitation box="[663,798,1265,1289]" captionStart="FIGURES 68 – 72" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1979,2002]" captionTargetBox="[212,1380,197,1961]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[212,1381,193,1961]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 68 – 72. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. spinosus female 68 – 72: 68. Dorsal view; 69. Head and pronotum; 70. Fore wing; 71. Mesonotum and metanotum; 72. Antenna." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280419/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
Figs 
<number box="[722,798,1265,1289]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" value="69.71">69, 71</number>
</figureCitation>
). The female sternites bear discal setae, and males lack sternal pore plates.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
